{id: 18, name: %Q|Mid-Town Green |, history: %Q|<p style="margin: 0.0px 0.0px 10.0px 0.0px; font: 10.0px Verdana;"><span style="letter-spacing: 0.0px;">Classified as a Neighborhood Park it serves as the recreational and social focus of the neighborhood.</span></p>
<p style="margin: 0.0px 0.0px 10.0px 0.0px; font: 10.0px Verdana;"><br />A former brickyard, the Midtown site was purchased in 1906 by Alfred Baxter, who founded te Baxter Laundry Co. her in 1876.&nbsp; Baxter used the Fountain &amp; Eastern site to expand his operation with a two-story building.&nbsp; After burning to 1975, the City cleared the site.&nbsp; In the 1980's, neighbors rallied to form the Midtown Neighborhood Assoc. and converted the vacant lot to the park.</p>|, latitude: 42.9654, longitude: -85.6509, park_size: 1.48, address: %Q|735 Fountain NE Grand Rapids|, vimeo_embed: %Q||, flickr_pool: %Q|1286590@N21|},
{id: 19, name: %Q|Monument Park|, history: %Q|<p style="margin: 0.0px 0.0px 10.0px 0.0px; font: 10.0px Verdana;"><span style="letter-spacing: 0.0px;">Established 1843</span></p>
<p style="margin: 0.0px 0.0px 10.0px 0.0px; font: 10.0px Verdana;"><span style="letter-spacing: 0.0px;">When the Army of the Cumberland announced their 1885 reunion would be held in Grand Rapids, the Kent County Soldeirs' Monument Association secured funds to erect a memorial.&nbsp; The memorial was dedicated on September 17, 1885, as part of the reunion's festivities.&nbsp; The monument was the first in the country to include a built-in fountain, and the first in the commemorate the role women played in the Civil War.&nbsp; The monument and fountain were renovated and repaired in 1959, and underwent a major restoration, competed in 2003.<br /></span></p>|, latitude: 42.9632, longitude: -85.6679, park_size: 0, address: %Q|Division and Fulton NE Grand Rapids|, vimeo_embed: %Q||, flickr_pool: %Q||},
