{id: 79, name: %Q|Plaster Creek Family Park/ Ken-O-Sha Park School/Trail|, history: %Q|<p>Established: 1923</p>
<p>Ken-O-Sha, "Water of the wall eyed pike," is the Native American name for Plaster Creek. &nbsp;In 1923, the park extended west as far as Division Ave. &nbsp;At this time, the City looked to acquire a 25-acre tract of creek land called Peck Woods. &nbsp;Soon accomplished, a road was built through the tract using local Scrip Labor. &nbsp;In 1963, Ken-O-Sha Elementary was built, and in 1972, the area near the school, with its two, quarter-mile trails, became the Ken-O-Sha Nature Park.</p>
<p>Legend states that Chief Black Bird took a Baptist missionary by canoe up Ken-O-Sha Creek to a waterfall, and told the Great Spirit who created this beauty. &nbsp;The missionary, while there, collected some of the gypsum there and set it to Detroit where a geologist confirmed the stone could be ground to plaster and sold. &nbsp;Long after Black Bird left the area, the name of the waters became Plaster Creek, the pollution therof banashing the Ken-O-Shay, or wall-eyed pike.&nbsp;</p>|, latitude: 42.9183, longitude: -85.6711, park_size: 152, address: %Q|2512 Buchanan SW Grand Rapids|, vimeo_embed: %Q||, flickr_pool: %Q||},
{id: 80, name: %Q|Roosevelt Park|, history: %Q|<p style="margin: 0.0px 0.0px 10.0px 0.0px; font: 10.0px Verdana;"><span style="letter-spacing: 0.0px;">Date Established: 1923</span></p>
<p style="margin: 0.0px 0.0px 10.0px 0.0px; font: 10.0px Verdana;">In 1922, the Roosevelt Business Men's Association petitioned the City Commission to create a park here, suggesting the site. &nbsp;A $13,380 fund was established ot purchase land from the Alabastine Company in 1923. &nbsp;By 1933, the merchants' group demanded improvements, and an investigation was launched into how Scrip Labor could be used to beautify the park. &nbsp;In the 1940's, plans for a community house were drawn up, and by 1943, Scrip Labor workers had erected the building</p>
<p style="margin: 0.0px 0.0px 10.0px 0.0px; font: 10.0px Verdana;">The park now provides access to Plaster Creek, has a Fitness Center &amp; playground, Basketball Program, and open field space.</p>
<p style="margin: 0.0px 0.0px 10.0px 0.0px; font: 10.0px Verdana;"><span style="letter-spacing: 0.0px;">&nbsp;</span></p>|, latitude: 42.9374, longitude: -85.6864, park_size: 8.25, address: %Q|739 VanRaalte SW Grand Rapids|, vimeo_embed: %Q|<iframe src="http://player.vimeo.com/video/26885411?title=0&amp;byline=0&amp;portrait=0" width="600" height="338" frameborder="0" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe>|, flickr_pool: %Q|1914497@N20|},
{id: 81, name: %Q|Westown Commons|, history: %Q|<p style="margin: 0.0px 0.0px 10.0px 0.0px; font: 10.0px Verdana;"><span style="letter-spacing: 0.0px;">Classified as a Neighborhood Park it serves as the recreational and social focus of the neighborhood. &nbsp;</span></p>
<p style="margin: 0.0px 0.0px 10.0px 0.0px; font: 10.0px Verdana;">NEWS<br />APRIL, 16, 2012</p>
<p style="margin: 0.0px 0.0px 10.0px 0.0px; font: 10.0px Verdana;"><span style="letter-spacing: 0.0px;">The Basketball Court at Westown Commons is currently a finalist to receive $15,000 through the Sprite Spark Parks program.&nbsp; <br /></span></p>
<p>Twenty five communities throughout the U.S. have a  chance to earn up to $15,000 for basketball court renovations.&nbsp; Westown  Commons Park in the City of Grand Rapids is one of the locations that  was selected by the National Recreation and  Park Association and Sprite.&nbsp; The amount of the grant award is  dependent upon the number of votes received.&nbsp; The top ten communities  earning the most votes will get $15,000, the second ten communities will  earn $10,000 and the lowest five communities will  earn $5,000.</p>
<p>To vote:&nbsp; go to <a href="http://www.spritesparkparks.com/" target="_blank">www.spritesparkparks.com</a></p>
<p>Register (create a username and password) on the site</p>
<p>In the &lsquo;Enter your code&rsquo; box at the top of the site, enter SPRITEPARKGR and this will give you one vote credit to use.</p>
<p>Then, click the &lsquo;vote now&rsquo; button (towards the middle of the screen) and use your one free vote for Westown Commons Park!</p>
<p>(You can vote using this method once per day from now until May 31.</p>
<p>You can also redeem Sprite My Coke Rewards points to vote (if you are a pop drinker and have a rewards points stash)</p>|, latitude: 42.9611, longitude: -85.6871, park_size: 1.07, address: %Q|752 Watson SW Grand Rapids|, vimeo_embed: %Q||, flickr_pool: %Q||},
{id: 82, name: %Q|Sweet Street|, history: %Q|<p>Sweet St. became a park in the summer of 2009.&nbsp; Formally part of Creston High School, the small playground was given to the City to become an official park.&nbsp; Thanks to the vision and efforts of Creston Neighborhood Association and community partners like Friends of Grand Rapids Parks, Amway and the City of Grand Rapids, the park was rehabbed and now includes a KaBOOM Playground.&nbsp; The community hopes to expand the park in the future.</p>|, latitude: 42.9918, longitude: -85.6575, park_size: 0.48, address: %Q|475 Sweet St Grand Rapids, MI 49503|, vimeo_embed: %Q||, flickr_pool: %Q||},
